1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,704
Welcome to Requirements Documentation and
Traceability.<break time="0.5s" />

2
00:00:03,704 --> 00:00:07,465
In this first lesson we’ll establish
requirements documentation as the

3
00:00:07,465 --> 00:00:11,118
"nervous system" of project delivery,
bridging strategic intent with

4
00:00:11,118 --> 00:00:13,353
operational reality.<break time="0.5s" />

5
00:00:13,353 --> 00:00:17,563
A project that is delivered on time and
under budget can still be a failure if it

6
00:00:17,563 --> 00:00:18,879
solves the wrong problem.

7
00:00:18,879 --> 00:00:23,303
This is where requirements documentation
comes in. It transmits strategic intent

8
00:00:23,303 --> 00:00:26,662
from the boardroom down to the
operational teams building the

9
00:00:26,662 --> 00:00:28,342
solution.<break time="0.5s" />

10
00:00:28,342 --> 00:00:32,665
Accurate requirements are critical
because they define the "what" before we

11
00:00:32,665 --> 00:00:34,008
worry about the "how.".

12
00:00:34,008 --> 00:00:38,427
Poor requirements management is a primary
cause of project failure, leading to

13
00:00:38,427 --> 00:00:42,157
scope creep, budget overruns, and
products that no one uses.<break

14
00:00:42,157 --> 00:00:42,960
time="0.5s" />

15
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:47,739
Documentation, in this context, is the
"single source of truth." It’s a codified

16
00:00:47,739 --> 00:00:51,913
agreement between the business
stakeholders, who possess the need, and

17
00:00:51,913 --> 00:00:55,906
the technical teams, who possess the
solution.<break time="0.5s" />

18
00:00:55,906 --> 00:01:00,014
Without this rigorous documentation, the
project plan is built on sand.<break

19
00:01:00,014 --> 00:01:00,771
time="0.5s" />

20
00:01:00,771 --> 00:01:04,177
To create this high-quality
documentation, we need to adopt a

21
00:01:04,177 --> 00:01:07,923
specific mental approach known as the
"Business Analysis Mindset.".

22
00:01:07,923 --> 00:01:11,712
This is a way of thinking that
prioritizes value creation over simple

23
00:01:11,712 --> 00:01:14,832
adherence to templates or
processes.<break time="0.5s" />

24
00:01:14,832 --> 00:01:19,700
Too often, analysts view documentation as
a check box exercise. The Business

25
00:01:19,700 --> 00:01:24,634
Analysis Mindset flips this perspective.
It views documentation as a tool for

26
00:01:24,634 --> 00:01:26,581
creating shared understanding.

27
00:01:26,581 --> 00:01:31,427
It asks us to look beyond the immediate
request and understand the root cause. It

28
00:01:31,427 --> 00:01:35,727
requires us to practice "holistic
thinking," considering how a change in

29
00:01:35,727 --> 00:01:39,604
one area, like software, impacts people,
processes, and the wider

30
00:01:39,604 --> 00:01:41,663
organization.<break time="0.5s" />

31
00:01:41,663 --> 00:01:45,362
This mindset ensures alignment across
diverse stakeholders and preserves

32
00:01:45,362 --> 00:01:49,374
organizational memory, ensuring that
critical knowledge outlasts the temporary

33
00:01:49,374 --> 00:01:51,823
nature of the project team.<break
time="0.5s" />

34
00:01:51,823 --> 00:01:55,757
To ground these concepts in reality,
we'll follow a single case study

35
00:01:55,757 --> 00:02:00,211
throughout this course. We'll act as a
Senior Business Analyst consultant at a

36
00:02:00,211 --> 00:02:01,947
